A Republican strategy to counter the re-election of Obama
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Centre Brennan sees it as a myth, saying that electoral fraud is rare in the United States that the number of people killed by lightning.
Moreover, the Republican lawyers have identified as 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: These new provisions will affect negatively the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the American states are responsible for the organization of the federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of American governments from 2009 passed new laws making it more difficult for the registration process or vote.
This phenomenon has grown after the elections in November 2010 which saw add 675 new Republican officials in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced during the year of 2011.
The new electoral laws require that voters present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
Moreover, these laws also reduce the periods of polls, invalidate the right to register as a voter on polling day and withdraw to citizens with a criminal record their right to vote.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state required voters to present a photo identification card.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
The United States Supreme Court upheld in 2008 the constitutionality of the law of Indiana.
Republican authorities clamoured to extend the practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo identification card.
It is important to note that, unlike the Quebec, American citizens do not have universal identity card as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo identification cards issued by a government agency of their state.
Moreover, five million new voters in 2012 does not have such an identity document.
However, it often costs more than one hundred dollars to obtain the required ID card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
Indeed, 25 percent of African-Americans, 15% of those earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters 18 to 29 years do not have the required photo ID card.
Much more.
Students, voters considered voting for candidates more Democrats, are not allowed in several states to use their photo identification card issued by their institution.
However, these same States allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use for voting cards issued by these clubs.
Prior to 2004, no state requires proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to introduce such a requirement.
In 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
However, it appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators have sponsored in 2011 laws abolishing registration of voters on polling day in eight states.
Moreover, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general election, the voter registration campaigns have helped to save about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have driven down by 17% rate of registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states to reduce the period of advance voting.
For example, in the general election of 2008 in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, while they accounted for only 13% of voters in the state.
The same was true with Hispanics.
They accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In return, the whites who accounted for 76% of voters represented only 46% of the electorate voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed to the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the Democratic governors vetoes.
The Advocate General of the United States intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo identification card.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undoubtedly make more difficult the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of laws that have been passed and they see it as an obvious goal to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A report by the Brennan Center for 2011 shows that the states that have adopted such laws account for 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes in the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: These new provisions will affect negatively the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will undermine the American democratic system.

