But each time, a central authority control and trade deals.
With Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are both custodians of the book of accounts, auditors, issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does this network?
Each transaction between two users is actually between two e-mail addresses in the manner of an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a dual-key encryption system.
The network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that traded bitcoins do exist in the book of public accounts, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers, and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege to add this line.
It is a hash phase of file, i.e. transformation of a large file into a single digital footprint and shorter.
"Computers are" the new transaction and add a number of "chop" before the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a special imprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number found, the other nodes easily check that this is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructiblement linked to the chain of all other transactions; any amendment would change the footprint.
If, to defraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining an orphan because the two have different fingerprint.
The computer has solved the challenge won 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this award is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible until one hundred millionth, leaving room...
The difficulty of the challenge is also raised to each increase in computing power.
