Pierre Noizat, also the author of a book on the currency, is a great believer in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real money) or a contactless mobile payment, but he uses to validate the Bitcoin transactions, which are less expensive.
The carrier operates over its identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement among merchants, who do not need to install new software or terminals.
All they need to provide an address, a phone can "photograph and recognize," said Pierre Noizat, which claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of questioning of hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
"It will take time for Bitcoin is needed, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
