A Constitution the forceps in Egypt
It is a new gamble of President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which grants him temporarily full powers, he decided to play everything.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted two months in this House to finish its work.
For almost two years ago that Egypt is based on a provisional text amended several times which weakens the institutional stability and led to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the divide in the country.
For his opponents, he persevered in his "autocratic style," continuing to "betraying its word" and "trampling the law."
On the side of his supporters, it ensures that it is a means to an end as soon as possible with the institutional and political crisis, accelerating the process of transition.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time which obliges the Brothers to abandon their plans to explain the text article by article, Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain a popular legitimacy and democratic, while the dispute raged across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for it, as he said in an interview with the US weekly Time.
As the use of a hasty vote takes the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, I keep the full powers," they would supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, Islamist majority, voted the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were missing.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, feeling they have not been able to express their views.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done likewise.
To ensure that the necessary quorum is reached, 11 people, substitute members, have been added in haste, yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles were voted.
Commentators have also amused by the fact that one of the only difference of the day has spoken around... the hour of prayer, some members of the committee felt that the pendulum of the Constituent Assembly was misadjusted.
The text, which was still being voted yesterday evening, includes 234 articles.
Objects from all sides, Article 2 is finally identical to that of the Constitution of 1971, stating that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafi parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to replace "principles" by "the rules," which would have allowed stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a sign of goodwill and respect for other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," replied the liberals, who see only a stroke of communication.
Because, according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They are, in particular Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University in an advisory role, particularly with regard to check the conformity of laws with sharia law.
According to the specialist in Egypt Sophie Pommier, it is worrying because "people called to decide are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the beginnings of a theocracy. "
The fears of Liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next president of the university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"For the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, it remains within the framework of the state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema but academics, some trained in the French system "moderates Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that "there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrowed religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" including [Islamic jurisprudence, ed].
And the question could arise in the future to what extent of civilian judges are competent to rule on it. "
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is widely criticized because of the powers it grants the president of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argue that they are significantly reduced in comparison to what they were under the old regime.
Another contentious point: The powers granted to the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but at a National Defence Council.
Nor will be banned the trial of civilians in military courts, as requested by the associations for the defence of human rights.
They are also expressed their concerns about the text, they deem liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, freedom of the press in particular.
Moreover, there is no longer echo the protection of women, "said Heba Morayef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was to speak last night on television, demonstrations are planned this afternoon.
The support of the head of state will march them, Saturday.

