This may be due to the fact that they have better inspectors?
No, definitely not, but I repeat, I don't have data for comparison.
However, it is also true that this country that we see as a model is also facing a series of problems.
Otherwise, they would have no incentive to cooperate with our institution, no?
With regard to national legislation, that has meant for you, as an institution, the amendment of the law on public procurement, its effects are already being felt?
This amendment entered into force relatively recently, it does not yet have an impact on our operations.
As we make a posteriori controls, we must reckon with a certain delay.
Our comments relate only, for the time being, the process of preparation of future controls - we have launched a new instrument "to detect risks of mismanagement" with which we have scrutinized nearly 14,000 public contracts - that these changes will be felt, of course, because the thresholds have been modified as well as the conditions of some types of tender procedures and so on.
So what do you consider the adoption of this law rather as an advantage or as an extra load for the administration?
I believe that this law is a step in the right direction, and I hope that the future will confirm this.
The problem that can happen is that these rules will become more severe, and that it is not possible to meet them.
Already under the previous regulations, the claimant (for example the regional council, in the case of the regional operational programmes) compelled controlled subjects to accept that any violation of the law on the markets means a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it really useful to make the law more severe in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack the system or abuse but not punish those who commit formal errors without consequence on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what is the solution to get by?
Look at where we are not going.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not disturb entrepreneurs with control of the so-called Švarc system - what does that mean?
The system is Švarc prohibited or authorized?
The law must be applied in one way or another, even if it prohibits anything, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority to inspect and demand respect for the law.
He may declare: "We are going to change the law and authorize it," but he could not say that we are going to act as if nothing had happened.
The law on markets has relatively strict rules on the formalities, precisely in order to protect the tender.
But it is also tragic that a bidder is eliminated only for cause of formal defects.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and it is, in my opinion, what is lacking at home.

