# genre=news sysid=Edinburgh origlang=cs docid=idnes.cz/2012/12/01/494025
Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second Member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had begun a close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the ensuing years has participated in a number of projects of the agency.
The road from Poland into space, however, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Poles passionate worked on space flights; they do not always meet understanding.
For example, I would like to mention the conference of A. Šternfeld at the astronomical observatory in Warsaw on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde book entitled "Introduction to astronautics."
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left listeners cold and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski became interested in its work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for his book "Introduction to astronautics."
The doctor Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) became a big propagator of astronomy and space travel.
He published hundreds of articles in newspapers Polish and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of astronautics of world renown, his contribution was notably rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the hidden side of the Moon.
As early as 1925 was built in Poland railway intended to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, there is neither the author nor the details of this project.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or curb railway.
The only information known about this railway are those of the press at the time.
In 1933, Polish artillery began to devote themselves to the rockets.
The research was conducted by the institute Komórka en Automobielbedrijf Tromp Uzbrojenia in collaboration with teachers Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
From the documents kept that this research had reached the stage of testing.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, research were interrupted.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - Torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two projects were directed military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all plans to use the technique of rockets were carried out by the Scientific Advisory Committee ("provisional TYMCZASOWY Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), who coordinated all work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other work on the aircraft were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is a question of a company in the November issue of the journal Problem 1954, in which four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to astronautics
At that time, projects of artificial satellites had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research was in the future.
At the beginning of the year 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) deployed efforts to enter the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He retained his position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the ATP brought a significant contribution to the successful development of the meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a range of 1,800 metres had an 80 cm long and weighed just under 5 kg.
Subsequently was built an improved version, RM-1A and, in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage rocket RM-2 were started in the desert of Bledov.
The rocket had a length of 1.4m and weighed probably 11.5 kg.
The prototype after ought to be able to make concrete scientific work - the rocket RM-34 ought to have a range of up to 14.5 km and serve to observe the wind aloft.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965, succeeded the first RM-type rockets.
The rocket, designed with two floors, had a total of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the size of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 per litre, whereas in Meteor-1B this volume was $0.34 per litre and Meteor-1C 0.62 per litre.
The maximum range of all these types of gear was 37 km.
In the period 1965-1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aviation institute, the first flight trials began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Later versions were built Meteor-2H and Meteor-3.
It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland at the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960, and the creation of a national committee COSPAR two years later.
Under the programme Interkosmos, Poland has also been involved in space exploration on the artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut.

