The repeal of the law on the public work is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court has repealed the law on public works.
This decision has raised in the public opinion a heated discussion.
Undoubtedly, it is interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
The economic systems geared towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalization, are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
This means that the different economic entities, as well as the national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of freedom of trade and the free movement (unlimited) of private capital ally to a rampant financial speculation.
The huge differences in the price of labour (wages) generate tension on prices.
It should be put under this term the following meaning: A producer tries by the importation of goods sold cheaply to withstand economic competition in "making it more expensive," the price of a competitor, in order to remove a larger share of the market and thereby increase its own profits.
Large-scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: Either transferring production abroad, or buy cheap or disappear. The result is a high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high in comparison to other economies.
Given that the private capital has no responsibility for the social point of view and thereby responsibility vis-à-vis the unemployment that it generates social charges of the State necessarily increase.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of Messrs. contractors to pay taxes and to compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole of society in the race for profit.
This situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistics.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital in the different economies create a situation in which the governments of various countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own people in order to attract foreign capital.
In other words, governments are putting their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking account of the social collapse.
This occurs mainly in the amendments of the laws in force.
The goal is to compel economically its own people to accept the dictates of the price of private capital, particularly in the area of wages.
This happens partly by a system of economic constraints in case of long-term unemployment and the restriction of the rights of workers in the field of labour legislation.
The result is a growing poverty and deepening of differences between the rich and the poor.
In Germany, there are for years points of public distribution of food for the poor who cannot meet their needs with their own work.
There are already by million the number of these people.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for employees receive such salaries that the State is obliged to pay a premium to reach the minimum subsistence level.
Such a scandal, for example, has been updated in the case of employees working as auxiliaries to the federal parliament.
The cost-saving measures of virtually all the southern Member States of the EU are, without doubt, a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century) or to eke out with poverty wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day the private capital to invest in their country.
Here we need to ask the question: Where will this capital?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will rise from one country to another; this capital may not come, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or African will continue to work for a fraction of a European wage.
This also applies to all of Latin America.
The liberal theory and the media claim to have enough of it, that the State cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the command economy led to an economic disaster.
Private capital is very much in the idea that the state may not intervene in the economy by regulatory interventions.
The question then becomes whether private capital does not influence and, even, does not run today, according to its own selfish interests, politics, and by the same, the entire state.
The answer to this question is certainly yes.
The proof is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby and present in all states.
The result is a desperate situation occurring in the field of corruption, by granting mutual benefits in the legislation, where everything is wrong but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that, because of the lack of financial resources, the national ministries delegate the preparation of draft laws to law firms closely tied to the industry.
These bills are then adopted in the Bundestag.
The entire power comes not from the people, as the Western-style constitutions but powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that democracies oriented towards liberalism are now quickly face the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "the crisis of the Roman Empire at the time of Caesar and Pompey": "The State had long been deteriorating and functions were assigned by violence.
The blows of bribes, favors received illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
The kickbacks and corruption were spreading without limits and the people went to the elections with votes already sold... "..." The honest people do not seek to obtain functions, the result was once the State was 8 months without consuls... "'It really began to say that the cure for this difficult situation was an autocracy and that he had to choose an energetic man..." It is true that Pompey Appianos had in mind, but it is Caesar who transformed irreversibly democracy in absolutist regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, today's society is based on the preference of the personal benefit, without regard for the interests of society as a whole.
In essence, the private capital is no longer able to understand and to advance the interests of society as a whole.
As a result, today as in the past, an unprecedented decadence elites, without any effort to conduct in-depth reforms.
We must therefore seek the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in unscrupulous liberalization of economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the current state of affairs, we can consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal democracies such as some sort of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites completely ignore the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the social and humanitarian crises that we are now witnesses as well as crimes against humanity as we know them by recent and ancient history.
The repeal of the law on the public work is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both internationally and domestically, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is systemic.
The solution is subject to socio-political reforms, which will strengthen the capital investment of the state in the economy, will increase the influence of citizens on the government, and will weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the State.

