The film Argo: When things are going badly wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of demonstrators composed of Islamist students stormed the US embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer to the US administration of positive outcome, it could not, in effect, abandon the Shah, because it would have severely shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was able to obtain the release of the hostages.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, shot even worse later by the fiasco of the attempt to rescue hostages by force.
Diplomats kidnapped were eventually released 444 days later, following negotiations held by the Algerian government.
Their fate in the United States provoked a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian sentiment.
The Iranian debacle contributed greatly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, the actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory in America.
Just before it is occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After twists complicated, they found themselves in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran through a whirlwind coverage: They left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew came to locations for the shooting of a film with great spectacle of science fiction.
Combination of gender
The plan of the exfiltration expert Tony Mendez required collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines were state of this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictitious production company had real offices.
The details of the operation were long secret, the film is based on the recollections of Tony Mendez.
The film is an unusual combination of Affleck of several genres.
It is a part of a political thriller designed realistically but also a "caper movie," the story of a successful coup, treachery - such as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen.
Successive moods: Sequences of Tehran in the documentary-style (subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of the events and the way in which, thanks to these photos, these same situations were recorded in the film, there is no great differences)
Lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a bit of exaggeration.
And then scenes of the headquarters of the CIA and other agencies with men dressed discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career so remarkable.
Actor ridiculed, he became a respected director and acting ceased to be ironic comments.
ARGO is his third feature film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also the first film Affleck who does not take place in his home city of Boston.
The meaning of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that would put his first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck is also proof of the sense of the atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran "is required" by Canada.
The best scenes from the film takes place in the streets, in the reconstruction of actual facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability arising when suddenly, in a given place, is writing a page of history.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the false film crew in the Tehran bazaar.
Too much in too many places shares
The director had to settle for a subject that does in fact that few exciting scenes, the film sense of the term.
He is doing very well, he adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at the Tehran airport is ruled out by a telephone call in America and the continued on the runway are quite far-fetched).
The weakness of Argo lies in its character dispelled, due to the need to show too many things to too many different locations.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are utterly charming in their role as Hollywood cooperators, their characters have deserved greater attention and it is not, far from it, the only in this case.
