People can report until the end of the year another incredible idea of "the workshop of the EU."
"The vote will take place before the end of the month of February 2013," informed Nacher.
Among the EU's controversial regulations is found, for example, the obligation to add components bio fuels, which has harmful effects on the environment, or the prohibition of the use of reliable mercury thermometers, simply because they contain a relatively small amount of a hazardous substance or the directive on the size of the cages chickens, which has led to an increase in the price of eggs.
Critics have also been made in the past against the ban on the use of the term "spreadable butter" or withdrawal from the sale of conventional light bulbs.
Quality bananas must have a size of 14 centimetres.
The European administration reacts often under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose applications are usually held in Brussels by a state or group of states (and the Czech Republic currently imposes applications of its banks by threatening to use its veto).
The interests of pressure groups are also, for example, the origin of the fact that in the Union, bananas should not be larger than 14 cm or submit an "abnormal curvature."
The European Commission has defended by arguing that it was only harmonize national standards non-homogeneous, complicating trade.
Standards for fruit and vegetables were relaxed despite the opposition of some States, claiming that the existing directives wasteful of foodstuffs.
The first prize will be awarded in this investigation to the EU regulation of last year, according to which must appear on balloons a warning stating that children under the age of 8 should not inflate without adult supervision.
The EU has referred to an American investigation, according to which the balloons are among the toys, the leading cause of death of children by suffocation.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 to blow in the trumpets of fair.
Here, too, it was strange ideas.
The following rule concerning the EU officials themselves is quite absurd: Because of the sensitivity of the topic for Greece, any person with an official function within the EU cannot use the name "Macedonia" and should instead talk of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the association "Laissez Faire" of liberal economists, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com appointed in this investigation, in addition to certain absurdities mentioned above, the EU's rules on the volume of reserves of food products on the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for the reserves of food products that can be found on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic was second, for example, the volumes set for canned mushrooms and risked, therefore, a heavy fine.
The organizers of the survey found merit in the idea of paying money to certain countries because they have no access to the sea and the idea of giving a subsidy for the granting of subsidies.
These ideas, however, are not from Brussels but in Prague.
"The fact of not having sea we handicaps.
We are going to ask the European Union a refund. "Thus expressed in the fall of 2004, the Minister of Agriculture at the time Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD).
He argued that, as a result of our production of wheat, and following the so-called "interventionist" purchases, the State was found with full stocks that he had to then export.
According to Palas, the EU would have had to pay millions of euros, because the Czech Republic is far from the ports.
In the end, the European Commission responded positively to the request of the Czech Republic and organized a tender for the purchase of wheat from countries without access.
Subsidies for grants to municipalities have been proposed by the Ministry of Local Development headed by the Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), they should, in effect, be used to write applications for grants from Brussels.
The EU said: "The bizarre regulations are rare."
If the regulations are often criticised in the Member States, according to many experts, efforts by the EU in terms of regulation and improving the effectiveness of the functioning of the Union as well as in the area of its overall development, rather deserve praise.
More serious is, for example, according to the experts, the problem of the use of EU grants for projects that have absolutely nothing to do with the strengthening of European integration, but which have been imposed by the Member States in the budget negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic should, like other countries of the Union, fighting in Brussels for the right to use specific names for these traditional products (fight it does not always winner) raises strong emotions among the Czechs.
If after six years of battle against the Germans and the Austrians, Czechs have successfully defended the name "Olomoucké tvarůžky," for which the name "Tuzemský rum," which dates back at home in the 19th century, our producers had to replace it with the name "Tuzemák."
Only the alcohol-based products of sugar cane, and not based on sugar beet, may bear the name of rum.
In the official list of registered products from the EU, there are today in the company of world known as Feta cheese or Gorgonzola, Lübeck marzipan or Parma ham, biscuits of Karlovy Vary ("Karlovarské suchary"), and of carp in Třeboň Pohořelice ("Pohořelický Třeboňský kapr has") and hops in Žatec ("Žatecký chmel").
The gingerbread Pardubice ("Pardubický perník") and cakes called "Cornets of Hořice" ("hořické trubičky") can also be proud of their Community trade mark.

