The architects of the firm MVRDV prove that the true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. For proof, just look at Spijkenisse and the mountain of books newly erected - 2 photos
"I think it's funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," said Lisette Verhaig, a shopper on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist in a large company next door, said: "Yes, it is actually nice, this building."
But I wonder why we still need today a library.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, nobody will voluntarily in one of these libraries elderly, no?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom community that is not attractive to the gates of Rotterdam, holds a record enough.
The town of 80,000 souls has the lowest rate of education of the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons in the brain drain, the city decided a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the shadow seven bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty small reinforced concrete painted miniatures.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
Thus, the city authorities have realized that there was only one way to retake control of the statistics: The construction of a library!
Winy Maas, the office of architects MVRDV Rotterdam, master charts "bold and creator of buildings full of spirit and often cynical, accepted the project with his usual unflappability and ran in the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a sneer on his face.
And while the members of the jury is still watching, confused and shrugging our shoulders, Maas, the brash, empila his books of choice by order of size to make it a pyramid, and ended his speech buttressed arguments by activists: "Common dear!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros has sprung up.
The building is part of a revitalization project also includes an underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and stepped houses for a total of 50 homes.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second "Best Library of NL 2012."
Moreover, the project has been selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this small town dull, which until now had nothing more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian zone and a mayor of a staggering ugliness, whose white façades suggest they support a dairy, was developed by a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long road to reading
First impression: El Dorado book under bell to cheese.
Admittedly, a lift takes you through the heart of the massive, but the real joy of reading and architecture are open to you when you stroll through the floor of the building to the discovery of its topography.
Interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floors and elegant streetlights unequivocally speak the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
There is already in the public benches, dogs and small boys and girls who play the ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally, the stacks are located along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," explained Willy Maas.
We have completely changed the classic spatial configuration and open spaces of reading from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been skillfully constructed: In the middle are the offices, the library Internet, the chess club, the centre for the environment and the building's technical center.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes panelling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes the banisters.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers building hardened do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," said Joop Trouborst, head of the project to the commune of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
Thus, one day we found in a farming business center with an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, has been used for years of the synthetic membrane of a millimetre thick as substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It is cheap and it is gaining time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then we can throw it.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, thick plates of four centimeters.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark material, homogeneous and resistant, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports footwear.
At the top of the 105 walks is the summit of the mountain.
After nearly 500 metres, the literary café offers a breathtaking view of the city, but also of the Dutch nuggets and potted ficus.
They create an atmosphere, but above all, they contribute to the maintenance of the ideal level of humidity of the literary mountain.
New donations for the soul
"It is unbelievable, but despite all glass surfaces, this building is a model project in ecology," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is settled by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun shines little time inside, even in good weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted wrong in relation to the glass facade of sun visors, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
Completely automated blinds can do the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already risky to enter the new library.
Lisette Verhaig also was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, describes the Boekenberg as "the soul finally found" of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen has been invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This has helped to fill the gaps in the library, which was not yet fully-stocked (today, there are 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The shelves are overflowing from all sides.
For the architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a library half empty."
"I think our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and the new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it is only for decoration. "
Thus, MVRDV reached discipline mistress called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity."
Spijkenisse wrote a new page of literary history.
Although it may seem young and poorly educated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.

